Networking Devices
This repository contains notes and explanations of common networking devices used in computer networks. These devices help connect computers, manage data traffic, and enable communication between different networks.
Devices Covered
Hub
A hub is a basic networking device that connects multiple computers in a network. It broadcasts incoming data to all connected devices without checking the destination.
Switch
A switch connects devices within a Local Area Network (LAN). It forwards data only to the intended device using MAC addresses, making communication faster and more efficient.
Router
A router connects different networks and directs data packets between them using IP addresses. It is commonly used to connect a home or office network to the Internet.
Modem
A modem converts digital data from a computer into signals that can travel over communication lines and vice versa. It acts as a bridge between an ISP and a local network.
Access Point (AP)
An access point provides wireless connectivity to devices, allowing them to join a wired network through Wi-Fi.
Bridge
A bridge connects and filters traffic between two network segments, reducing unnecessary data transmission.
Repeater
A repeater receives weak network signals, amplifies them, and retransmits them to extend network coverage.
Gateway
A gateway acts as an entry and exit point between different networks that may use different communication protocols.
Firewall
A firewall monitors and controls incoming and outgoing network traffic based on predefined security rules, helping protect networks from unauthorized access.


